Navigate to other release versions of Doxee Platform Business Designer

[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-7)

Decimal formats are used to define separators for large numbers or decimal separators. You can access and edit decimal formats in the left toolbar under "Other".

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

In the left area, you can add (local via + or external via folder icon), edit, or delete existing decimal formats. You can change the name and delete if you move the mouse over the name of the decimal format and select the corresponding icon in the black menu. On the right side you can edit the attributes of the decimal formats.

Saved decimal formats can be assigned to Dynamic Value elements in the Design View to format the output of the Dynamic Value. This can be done by selecting the type *number *and choose the defined decimal format in the selection under Format.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The possible attribute for decimal formats are:

**Attribute**

**Description**

Format name

A unique name to identify the decimal format in the template. If there is only one decimal format and the name is left empty, it will be considered the default and no name needs to be entered to reference it.

Decimal separator

A character used as decimal separator for numbers, e.g. to change from period to comma as decimal separator.

Group separator

A character which is used as group separator for numbers, e.g. a dot for all n digits. The number of digits after which the separator is added are defined by the format of the dynamic value, e.g. ###.##0.00.

Infinity

A character which is used instead of the default infinity character ().

Minus sign

A character which is used instead of the default minus sign (-).

**Attribute**

**Description**

Not-a-number description

A character which is used instead of the default Not a Number character (NaN).

Percent sign

A character which is used instead of the standard percent sign (%).

Per-mille sign

A character which is used instead of the standard per-mille sign ().

Zero digit

A character which is used instead of zero (0).

Pattern separator

A character which is used instead of the standard format separator (;).
